x4freetext: High intensity neutron pulse is produced every
2.4 s from spallation reactions induced by a 20-GeV/c
proton beam incident on a 80x80x60 cm3 lead target.
A water layer of 58 mm cools down the target.
Nearly symmetrical Gaussian-shaped profile at sample
position. In the eV region the width of this Gaussian
profile is about 5 mm, yielding a total diameter of
At the irradiation position (185m) a high instantaneous
intensity neutron beam covers the energy range from
thermal to relativistic energies with a nearly
isolethargic distribution between 1 eV and few tens of
keV. A neutron flux of 5E+5 n/cm2 between thermal and
10 MeV is produced by each proton pulse of the nominal
Precise energy dependence of the neutron fluence in
the energy range of this work (1-500 eV) was determined
from measurements with the 6Li-based silicon monitor.
The neutron capture detection system consists
of segmented Total Absorption Calorimeter made of 40
Ba-F2 crystals with B-10 loaded carbon fiber capsules.
Nearly 100 % detection efficiency for capture cascades
with energy resolutions of 16% at 662 keV and 6% at
Neutron sensitivity and  sample activity were reduced
by  C12-H20-O4-(Li-6)2 neutron absorber between sample
and crystals. Performance of TAC was investigated with
calibration sources and reference Au-197(n,g) cross
section and by Monte Carlo simulations.
The energy calibration is obtained from the amplitude
distribution of the slow component measured for
185 m flight path ( TAC from spallation source).
The calculation of the fraction F-BIF of the beam
incident on the sample (beam interception factor) is
accomplished by means of the saturated resonance method
measuring a thick gold sample of the same diameter as
the Np one. The thickness of the sample and the gold
cross section at the 4.9-eV resonance are such that all
(with some corrections) incident neutrons are captured
and therefore the number of capture reactions occurring
at the flat top of the resonance provides directly the
total number of incident neutrons at that energy.A beam
interception factor of 19.1% was found in agreement
with the expected value from the information available
Accuracy of evaluated shape of the neutron flux with
better than 2% in the region below a few keV.

Measured capture yields were analyzed using SAMMY code,
following the iterative sequential fit method in RRR.

The resonance analysis was carried out as well without
the normalization to transmission, leading both
analysis methods to results in agreement within 6%.
